	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-634604 post type-post status-publish hentry category-financial-services category-investment-banking category-legal tag-bank-of-italy tag-banking-and-financial-institutions tag-european-central-bank tag-european-sovereign-debt-crisis-2010 tag-fabio tag-genoa-italy tag-italy tag-monte-dei-paschi-di-siena-spa tag-rome-italy per-fabio des-banking-and-financial-institutions des-european-sovereign-debt-crisis-2010 org-bank-of-italy org-european-central-bank org-monte-dei-paschi-di-siena-spa geo-genoa-italy geo-italy geo-rome-italy news_keywords-bank-of-italy news_keywords-banking-and-finance news_keywords-euro-crisis news_keywords-european-central-bank news_keywords-fabio news_keywords-genoa news_keywords-italy news_keywords-monte-dei-paschi-di-siena news_keywords-rome" id="post-634604">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Italian Banks Are the Weakest Performers in E.C.B. Review</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Gaia Pianigiani			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-26T18:57:57+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 26, 2014 2:57 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 26, 2014 2:57 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/italian-banks-are-the-weakest-performers-in-e-c-b-tests/" data-title="Italian Banks Are the Weakest Performers in E.C.B. Review" data-description="Nine Italian lenders had capital shortfalls at the end of 2013 and four of them still must raise more capital, including Monte dei Paschi di Siena.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/26/business/dbpix-eubanks-siena/dbpix-eubanks-siena-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/26/business/dbpix-eubanks-siena/dbpix-eubanks-siena-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/26/business/dbpix-eubanks-siena/dbpix-eubanks-siena-blog480.jpg" id="100000003197953" width="480" height="276" alt="Headquarters of Monte dei Paschi in Siena, Italy. The bank must raise â¬2.1 billion, the European Central Bank said, the largest of any individual bank covered by the review."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="276"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Headquarters of Monte dei Paschi in Siena, Italy. The bank must raise â¬2.1 billion, the European Central Bank said, the largest of any individual bank covered by the review.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stefano Rellandini/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/ecb-stress-test-finds-13-banks-fall-short/">Just 13 Eurozone Banks Fail Test, in Possible Economic Turning Point</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ROME â Italyâs banking system had the highest number of lenders flunking the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank">European Central Bank</a>âs review of eurozone banks, reflecting the countryâs unremitting economic malaise.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Italyâs two largest banks, Unicredit and Intesa Sanpaolo, passed the tests comfortably. However, the central bank said that nine of the 15 Italian lenders under the review had capital shortfalls at the end of 2013 and four of them still must raise more capital, including Monte dei Paschi di Siena.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Considered the worldâs oldest continuously operating lender, Monte dei Paschi must raise 2.1 billion euros, or $2.7 billion, the largest of any individual bank covered by the review, released on Sunday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââItalian small banks are taking the toll of the longstanding recession,ââ said Pietro Reichlin, professor of economics at LUISS University in Rome. ââTheir conditions are aggravated by credits they canât recover, and the only clients who are seeking credit are the ones in difficulty economic situations, and thus risky loans.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Bank of Italy, the countryâs central bank, emphasized that the shortfall represented only 0.2 percent of Italyâs gross domestic product, and that Italian banks underperformed only in a severe macroeconomic contraction that is very unlikely to happen.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Bank of Italy added that the Italian economy is stagnant and that the European Central Bankâs stress test model has more serious consequences for countries with already weak growth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Italy in August reported that its economy, the third largest in the eurozone after Germany and France, had contracted 0.2 percent from April through June, compared with the first quarter of 2014. That was the second quarterly decline in a row, meeting the most common definition of a recession.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fabio Panetta, deputy director general of the Bank of Italy, underlined that other European countries had injected much more public money into their banks, while Italy had granted only â¬4 billion in state aid to Italian banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââThe results confirm the overall resilience of the Italian banking system, notwithstanding repeated shocks to the Italian economy in the past six years,ââ the Bank of Italy said in a statement, highlighting how the global financial crisis, the sovereign debt crisis and Italyâs double-dip recession had weighed on the banking system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Franco Bruni, professor of international monetary economics at Bocconi University in Milan, noted that over the course of this year ââthe Italian banking system has fixed its troubles more than others, both through capital increases and important measures that have already been approved.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââBut Italian banks mirror the country,ââ Mr. Bruni said. ââItaly has a hard time changing, reforming itself and becoming more efficient.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Italyâs Finance Ministry on Sunday expressed confidence in the banksâ capability to cover the residual shortfall, which the European Central Bank said totaled â¬3.3 billion, most of it attributed to Monte dei Paschi. That bank said it had hired <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=UBS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about UBS A.G">UBS</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=C&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Citigroup Inc">Citigroup</a> as financial advisers to help it devise a plan to raise capital and evaluate ââall strategic alternatives.ââ That potentially could include a merger with a stronger bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The second-biggest deficit was at Genoa-based Carige, which still needs to raise â¬814 million. The European Central Bank also reported shortfalls at two local banks, Banca Popolare di Milano and Banca Popolare di Vicenza. But the Bank of Italy said that those two lenders in September had made up their gaps with additional measures to strengthen their capital base.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Economists argue that Italy needs to consolidate its banking sector and that lenders need to be more proactive in helping businesses plan and grow. But Italy also needs help from its neighbors, some economists said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The cabinet of Italyâs prime minister, Matteo Renzi, has drafted a mix of tax and spending cuts in its budget plan for 2015, which increases its deficit, though by less than it had originally forecast. The spending plan faces a verdict this week by the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_union/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the European Union.">European Union</a>, which is to decide whether to grant Italy and France more flexibility on deficit and debt rules.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââA single country canât do more than this, we need a stronger common European action,ââ Tito Boeri, professor of economics at Bocconi University, said. ââWhat Italy certainly needs to do is make its banks less influenced by politics.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Boeri referred to the troublesome financial and political saga of the Tuscan lender, Monte dei Paschi, that tapped the market for â¬5 billion in June. It still needs to repay â¬750 million out of a â¬4.1 billion state bailout loan that it sought in 2012 to restore a dire financial situation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Founded in 1472, Monte dei Paschi&#8217;s expansion in the years before the financial crisis, and derivatives deals undertaken by the former management to conceal big losses, led it to seek the government rescue.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââI see it as a bank in convalescence,ââ Salvatore Rossi, director general of the Bank of Italy, said of Monte dei Paschi. ââIt entered a strengthening program with the E.C.B. and the Italian government, and during its convalescence, it was asked to run a 100-meter race, and it has suffered.ââ</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/ecb-stress-test-finds-13-banks-fall-short/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/27/business/27eubank-1/27eubank-1-thumbWide.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Just 13 Banks Fail E.C.B. Stress Test, in Possible Economic Turning Point" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/ecb-stress-test-finds-13-banks-fall-short/?ref=dealbook">Just 13 Banks Fail E.C.B. Stress Test, in Possible Economic Turning Point</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By JACK EWING</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">The European Central Bank said of the 130 banks it reviewed, only 13 lacked sufficient capital to withstand a severe crisis. But some analysts question the rigor of the exam.</p>
			</div>
			
